{
  "doc_id": "44372",
  "text": "Rapid advances are being made in the molecular characterization and phylogenetic comparison of Baylisascaris species [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . The complete mitochondrial genomes of B. procyonis [CITATION_6] , B. schroederi, B. ailuri, and B. transfuga [CITATION_7] have been published, and mitochondrial and nuclear markers have been developed for B. columnaris [CITATION_8] . Molecular tests have also been developed for environmental investigations and for the diagnostic identification of Baylisascaris DNA in definitive host fecal samples and tissue samples from biopsies and autopsies performed in clinical cases of NLM [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . Specialists are usually required for larval identification, although even their experience is not always sufficient to differentiate B. procyonis from other types of larvae, particularly within the genus Baylisascaris. Ideally, molecular tests would provide a rapid identification of B. procyonis, separating it from closely related species, including B. columnaris [CITATION_13] , and would also serve as a tool for epidemiologic studies and sanitary management, considering the close association between raccoons and humans that can lead to the contamination of soil, water, and food with eggs of Baylisascaris [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] . These tests are also very important for host-based or environmental diagnosis in cases in which captive animals may be at risk [CITATION_16] .",
